<TITLE> Malaysian hockey admits to debt trouble </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KUALA LUMPUR, Jan 29 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The Malaysian Hockey Federation (MHF), which reportedly has less than $300 in its bank account, has debts of more than $500,000, according to local media. The MHF ran up the debts after hosting the recent Champions Trophy tournament involving the world's leading teams but said in a statement they would be able to solve their financial problems within two months. "We are currently waiting for some allocation and reimbursements from the National Sports Council, International Hockey Federation (FIH) and several sponsors who have committed for 2007-2008," the statement read. Over the past year, Malaysian sports have struggled to justify expensive investment for major events. Last July's Asian Cup soccer tournament, for which Malaysia was a co-host, failed to attract the aniticpated crowds while the Champions Trophy also struggled to stir public interest. MHF officials said they had yet to receive around $150,000 pledged by government agencies, sponsors and the FIH to help stage the tournamen
